Can anyone provide a quote where Trump directly stated to inject bleach into themselves?

What he did say was find a way to use ultraviolet light inside the body to kill the virus and to find someway of using a disinfectant to inject, but quickly corrected to a cleaning, inside the lungs to kill the virus.

Was he being sarcastic about these statements like he suggested, I highly doubt that but you can't just say something he didn't explicitly say as if he said it.

Now analysing the two above statements he said, from a purely scientific viewpoint, is there any evidence to suggest that those two options are viable (not stating that he knew that these treatments existed at the time) - which could potentially be utilised in severe cases by medical professionals?

Ultraviolet light has previously been used as a method of treating infection by irradiating a percentage of a persons blood to kill the virus (normally aorund 15%) back just over half a century ago. A paper came out more recently to suggest that this treatment should be looked into as a potential way to treat virus' and bacterial infections in the future, as they become more and more resistant to drugs.

Now we come on to injecting/cleaning the lungs out with a form of disinfectant. Now there are actual multiple types of disenfectants which can be used in a variety of different ways. Not all are bleach or lysol. There are treatments in the past using aerosolised alcohol (as alcohol is a disinfectant) as a way to treat fluid retention in the lungs caused by a pulmonary edema. However, if everyone wants to be really pedenatic about the use of the term inject, then there is a study in mammals and later clinical trials, which shows that the injection of quaternary ammonium compounds (also a type of disenfectant) can play a role in the control and treatment of virus' in the blood stream like HSV-1, HSV-2, and Vaccinia. Whether or not this treatment would be useful for a respiratory virus is yet to be seen, however it is plausible that an 'injection of a type of disinfectant' could legitimately be used as a way to treat virus.
